  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects real people. Growing up in a household where both parents had PhDs, I learned early that intelligence is often framed as a fixed trait, especially in technical fields. But as an electrician with a part-time job in New York, I've seen how this mindset plays out in everyday situations. When someone tells a kid they're 'not good at math,' it can shape their entire approach to problem-solving, even if they're capable. Stereotype threat isn't about being 'less smart'—it's about the anxiety of being labeled as someone who doesn't belong in a field they're actually trying to excel in. I've noticed this in my own life too; when I'm working on complex wiring projects, the fear of messing up can overshadow the actual task. Addressing it requires practical steps, not just lectures. For instance, creating environments where people feel safe to ask questions without judgment, or simply acknowledging that everyone starts somewhere. As someone who's struggled with depression, I know how important it is to reduce the pressure that comes from societal expectations. In STEM, where the stakes feel so high, we need to shift from 'you must be smart enough' to 'you can learn and grow.' It's not about changing the system overnight, but small, consistent efforts to build confidence and community. This is especially critical for kids who might not have access to the same resources as others. My own experience with board games and video games taught me that play can be a powerful tool for learning—so why not apply that mindset to STEM education? The answer isn't in abstract theories but in real, hands-on support that makes people feel seen and valued.",
